Data eXchange (EDX) was developed and is maintained by NETL-ORD \r\nas an online system to support internal coordination and collaboration \r\nas well as timely tech transfer of data-driven products across NETL's \r\nresearch portfolios, see \"[about NETL](http://netl.doe.gov/about)\" for more information. \r\n\r\n EDX coordinates historical and current data and information from a wide\r\n variety of sources to facilitate access to research that crosscuts \r\nmultiple NETL projects/programs.\r\n\r\nEDX provides external access to technical products and data published by NETL-affiliated research teams.\r\n\r\n NETL-affiliated researchers can use EDX's Collaborative Workspaces to \r\ncoordinate and share work with a variety of organizations and \r\ninstitutions in a secure environment.\r\n\r\n* * *\r\n###Why was EDX created? \r\n\r\n NETL recognized a need to improve coordination and reliable access to \r\ninformation and research products for our own research teams and amongst\r\n our collaborators, as well as improve dissemination (tech transfer) of \r\nresearch-driven products. By improving the efficiency of data access and\r\n data sharing, EDX facilitates a more rapid and comprehensive \r\nutilization of key data needs that crosscut multiple projects/program \r\nareas (CO2 storage, unconventional and conventional \r\nhydrocarbon systems, natural gas hydrates, etc.). Resources are organized by class and country.  Resolution varies spatially from 1 km to 1 degree (approximately 100 km) depending on the data source.  High spatial resolution datasets (1 km to 40 km cells) were modeled to support country or regional projects.  Where high resolution datasets were not available, data from NASA\u2019s Surface Meteorology and Solar Energy (SSE) version 6 database were used.  \r\n\r\nThe data represent total potential solar energy per year as a function of land area per solar class (`KWh/m\u00b2/day`).  Each solar class correlates to a specific `0.5 kWh/m\u00b2/day` range.  Energy is calculated by multiplying the productive land by the class, conversion efficiency and number of days per year.  In this case, a standard calendar year of 365 days was used.  The conversion efficiency rate applied was 10%.\r\n\r\n`E = Productive Land * kWh/m\u00b2/day * 365 days * 10% efficiency`\r\n\r\nThe solar data has been derived from solar data measured or modeled The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented due south at an angle from horizontal equal to the latitude of the collector location.\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_ These data provide monthly average and\r\n annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells \r\nof approximately 40 km by 40 km in size.  The solar resource value is \r\nrepresented as watt-hours per square meter per day for each month.  The \r\ndata were developed from NREL's Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) \r\nModel.  This model uses information on cloud cover, atmospheric water \r\nvapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to \r\ncalculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) \r\nfalling on a horizontal surface.   Existing ground measurement stations \r\nare used to validate the data where possible.  The modeled values are \r\naccurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid \r\ncell due to the uncertainties associated with meteorological input to \r\nthe model.  The local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a \r\nsingle grid cell as a result of terrain effects and other microclimate \r\ninfluences. "description": "_(Abstract):_  Monthly Average Solar Resource for flat-plate collectors tilted at latitude for Ghana.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Provide information on the solar resource potential for the data domain. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented horizontally.\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   These data provide monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximately 40 km by 40 km in size.  The solar resource value is represented as watt-hours per square meter per day for each month.  The data were developed from [NREL's](http://www.nrel.gov) Documentation of high resolution solar resource assessment (10km) for Nepal provided by DLR Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model.  This model uses information on cloud cover, atmospheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface.   Existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data where possible.  The modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell due to the uncertainties associated with meteorological input to the model.  The local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell as a result of terrain effects and other microclimate influences. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.",       "keyword": [        "GEF",         "GIS", "description": "_(Abstract):_  Monthly Average Solar Resource for 2-axis \r\ntracking concentrating collectors for Kenya.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Provide information on the solar resource \r\npotential for the data domain. The insolation values represent the \r\naverage solar energy available to a concentrating collector, such as a \r\ndish collector, which tracks the sun continuously.\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   These data provide monthly average and\r\n annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells \r\nof approximately 40 km by 40 km in size.  The solar resource value is \r\nrepresented as watt-hours per square meter per day for each month.  The \r\ndata were developed from [NREL's](http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL) Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) \r\nModel.  This model uses information on cloud cover, atmospheric water \r\nvapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to \r\ncalculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) \r\nfalling on a horizontal surface.   Existing ground measurement stations \r\nare used to validate the data where possible.  The modeled values are \r\naccurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid \r\ncell due to the uncertainties associated with meteorological input to \r\nthe model.  The local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a \r\nsingle grid cell as a result of terrain effects and other microclimate \r\ninfluences. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates \r\nincrease with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the \r\ncomplexity of the terrain.",       "keyword": [        "DNI", "description": "_(Abstract):_  A data set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period.\r\n\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   A TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year. The intended use is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years. Because they represent typical rather than extreme conditions, they are not suited for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location.",     }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Meteorology: typical meteorological year data for selected stations in Brazil from NREL",       "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each TMY is a data set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the NREL METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. The container file contains one TMY file for each selected station in the region, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   A TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year. The intended use is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years. Because they represent typical rather than extreme conditions, they are not suited for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location.", "description": "This shapefile represents seasonal summer average cold water depth recordings.\r\n\r\nThe cold water is defined by locating the depth that leads to the greatest average annual net power at each location when depth and its corresponding \u0394T are input into the power equation. This optimization balances power gained by obtaining colder water from deeper locations against power lost by transporting the water upward through a longer pipe. Input depth and temperature values are obtained from the Hybrid Coordinate Ocean Model (HYCOM) and are reported at discrete depth levels. The cut-off for maximum cold water depth is 1000 m.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). Solar radiation is modeled using the NREL METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. The container file contains one TMY file for each selected station in the region, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_ A TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year. The intended use is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years. Because they represent typical rather than extreme conditions, they are not suited for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location.",       "keyword": [        "GEF",         "Ghana",         "NREL",         "SWERA",         "TMY",         "UNEP",         "meteorologic"      ],       "modified": "2015-08-21T20:51:24Z",       "publisher": {        "@type": "org:Organization",         "name": "National Renewable Energy Laboratory"      },       "bureauCode": [        "019:20"      ],       "programCode": [        "019:000"      ],       "contactPoint": {        "@type": "vcard:Contact",         "fn": "Nicholas Langle",         "hasEmail": "mailto:nicholas.langle@nrel.gov"      },       "identifier": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/0db89086-5d83-4b59-9dd7-f4bad7ce871f",       "accessLevel": "public",       "accessURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/0db89086-5d83-4b59-9dd7-f4bad7ce871f/resource/6d8a5bcb-7225-4ad2-b34a-4d9a32937800/download/ghanatmy142.zip",       "format": "application/unknown",       "license": "https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/",       "dataQuality": true,       "distribution": [        {          "@type": "dcat:Distribution",           "description": "Download Data",           "title": "Download Data",           "format": "ZIP",           "downloadURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/0db89086-5d83-4b59-9dd7-f4bad7ce871f/resource/6d8a5bcb-7225-4ad2-b34a-4d9a32937800/download/ghanatmy142.zip",           "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Arizona High Resolution Wind Resource",       "description": "_Abstract:_  Annual average wind resource potential for the state of Arizona at a 50 meter height.    }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Continental United States Photovoltaic Low Resolution",       "description": "_Abstract:_  Monthly and annual average solar resource potential for the lower 48 states of the United States of America.\r\n\r\n_Purpose:_  Provide information on the solar resource potential for the United States of America lower 48 states. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented due south at an angle from horizontal equal to the latitude of the collector location.\r\n\r\n_Supplemental Information:_  This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximatley 40 km by 40 km in size. This data was developed from the Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model. The CSR model was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Maxwell, George and Wilcox (1998) and George and Maxwell (1999). This model uses information on cloud cover, atmostpheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. The cloud cover data used as input to the CSR model are an 7-year histogram (1985-1991) of monthly average cloud fraction provided for grid cells of approximately 40km x 40km in size. Thus, the spatial resolution of the CSR model output is defined by this database. The data are obtained from the National Climatic Data Center in Ashville, North Carolina, and were developed from the U.S. Air Force Real Time Nephanalysis (RTNEPH) program. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. The procedures for converting the collector at latitude tilt are described in Marion and Wilcox (1994). Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not avalible at a 40km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other micoclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain. \r\nUnits are in kilowatt hours per meter squared per day.\r\n\r\nOtherCitation Details:\r\n\r\nGeorge, R, and E. Maxwell, 1999: \"High-Resolution Maps of Solar Collector Performance Using A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1999 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Portland, ME. \r\n\r\nMaxwell, E, R. George and S. Wilcox, \"A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1998 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Albuquerque NM. \r\n\r\nMarion, William and Stephen Wilcox, 1994: \"Solar Radiation Data Manual for Flat-plate and Concentrating Collectors\". NREL/TP-463-5607, National Renewable Energy Laboratory, 1617 Cole Boulevard, Golden, CO 80401.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). This data was developed using the State University of New York/Albany satellite radiation model. This model was developed by Dr. Richard Perez and collaborators at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory and other universities for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Perez, et al. (2002). This model uses hourly radiance images from geostationary weather satellites, daily snow cover data, and monthly averages of atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the hourly total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. A modified Bird model is used to calculate clear sky direct normal (DNI). This is then adjusted as a function of the ratio of clear sky global horizontal (GHI) and the model predicted GHI. Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meteorological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not available at a 10km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 15% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other microclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.\r\n\r\nThis dataset uses geographic coordinate system GCS_North_American_1983\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). 2005)",       "description": "This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of 0.1 degrees in both latitude and longitude, or about 10 km in size. This data was developed using the State University of New York/Albany satellite radiation model. This model was developed by Dr. Richard Perez and collaborators at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory and other universities for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Perez, et al. (2002). This model uses hourly radiance images from geostationary weather satellites, daily snow cover data, and monthly averages of atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the hourly total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. A modified Bird model is used to calculate clear sky direct normal (DNI). This is then adjusted as a function of the ratio of clear sky global horizontal (GHI) and the model predicted GHI. Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meteorological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not available at a 10km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 15% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other microclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "description": "This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of 0.1 degrees in both latitude and longitude, or about 10 km in size. This data was developed using the State University of New York/Albany satellite radiation model.  This model was developed by Dr. Richard Perez and collaborators at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory and other universities for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Perez, et al. (2002). This model uses hourly radiance images from geostationary weather satellites, daily snow cover data, and monthly averages of atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the hourly total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. A modified Bird model is used to calculate clear sky direct normal (DNI).  This is then adjusted as a function of the  ratio of clear sky global horizontal (GHI) and the model predicted GHI.   Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meteorological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not available at a 10km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 15% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other microclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/9b8b14de-7ee5-4b81-ae15-ffda854446dd/resource/ad3e809b-dfe0-4ff0-a421-0ba8cc484600/download/lower48dnihighresolution.zip",           "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: United States Hydrogen Potential From Renewable Resources",       "description": "Estimate the potential for producing hydrogen from key renewable resources (onshore wind, solar photovoltaic, and biomass) by county for the United States. This study was conducted to estimate the potential for producing hydrogen from key renewable resources (onshore wind, solar photovoltaic, and biomass) by county in the United States and to create maps that allow the reader to easily visualize the results. To accomplish this objective, the authors analyzed renewable resource data both statistically and graphically utilizing a state-of-the-art Geographic Information System (GIS), a computer-based information system used to create and visualize geographic information.\r\n\r\nLand-use and environmental exclusions were applied to represent the most viable resources across the country. While wind, solar, and biomass are considered major renewable resources, other renewable energy resources could also be used for hydrogen production, thus contributing to hydrogen development locally and regionally. These additional resources include offshore wind, concentrating solar power, geothermal, hydropower, photoelectrochemical, and photobiological resources.\r\n\r\nThis study found that approximately 1 billion metric tons of hydrogen could be produced annually from wind, solar, and biomass resources in the United States. The greatest potential for producing hydrogen from these key renewable resources is in the Great Plains region. In addition, this research suggests that renewable hydrogen has the potential to displace gasoline consumption in most states if and when a number of technical and scientific barriers can be overcome.\r\n\r\n## License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "description": "This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of 0.1 degrees in both latitude and longitude, or about 10 km in size. This data was developed using the State University of New York/Albany satellite radiation model.  This model was developed by Dr. Richard Perez and collaborators at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory and other universities for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Perez, et al. (2002). This model uses hourly radiance images from geostationary weather satellites, daily snow cover data, and monthly averages of atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the hourly total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. The procedures for converting the collector at latitude tilt are described in Marion and Wilcox (1994). Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not avalable at a 10km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other micoclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Continental United States Global Horizontal Solar Resource 10km Resolution (1998 - 2005)",       "description": "This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of 0.1 degrees in both latitude and longitude, or about 10 km in size. This data was developed using the State University of New York/Albany satellite radiation model. This model was developed by Dr. Richard Perez and collaborators at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory and other universities for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Perez, et al. (2002). This model uses hourly radiance images from geostationary weather satellites, daily snow cover data, and monthly averages of atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the hourly total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data.  Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not available at a 10 km resolution.  As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 9% of a true measured value within the grid cell.  Due to terrain effects and other microclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell.  Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). Average)",       "description": "This shapefile represents the seasonal winter depth profile to reach water at a temperature of 14\u00baC.\r\n\r\nSea water cooling can be used for industrial or residential cooling needs where heat must be rejected. A typical resource for direct air-conditioning applications is no warmer than 8\u00baC, which has been established as a minimum value of interest for this study. Water at temperatures between 8\u00baC and 20\u00baC can be used to supplement air conditioning processes, or to reject heat from many other low temperature industrial processes. Water temperatures above 20\u00baC were not considered for this investigation as cost savings begin to break down as sea water temperature nears ambient temperatures. Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Building Component Library",       "description": "The Building Component Library (BCL) is the U.S. Department of Energy\u2019s comprehensive online searchable library of energy modeling building blocks and descriptive metadata. Novice users and seasoned practitioners can use the freely available and uniquely identifiable components to create energy models and cite the sources of input data, which will increase the credibility and reproducibility of their simulations.    The BCL contains components which are the building blocks of an energy model. They can represent physical characteristics of the building such as roofs, walls, and windows, or can refer to related operational information such as occupancy and equipment schedules and weather information. Each component is identified through a set of attributes that are specific to its type, as well as other metadata such as provenance information and associated files.    The BCL also contains energy conservation measures (ECM), referred to as measures, which describe a change to a building and its associated model. For the BCL, this description attempts to define a measure for reproducible application, either to compare it to a baseline model, to estimate potential energy savings, or to examine the effects of a particular implementation.    The BCL currently contains more than 30,000 components and measures. A faceted search mechanism has been implemented on the BCL that allows users to filter through the search results using various facets. Facet categories include component and measure types, data source, and energy modeling software type. All attributes of a component or measure can also be used to filter the results.",       "keyword": [        "BCL",         "building component library",         "building components",         "building efficiency",         "energy conservation measures",         "energy efficiency",         "energy modeling"      ],       "modified": "2015-08-21T20:50:47Z",       "publisher": {        "@type": "org:Organization",         "name": "National Renewable Energy Laboratory"      },       "bureauCode": [        "019:20"      ],       "programCode": [        "019:000"      ],       "contactPoint": {        "@type": "vcard:Contact",         "fn": "Nicholas Long",         "hasEmail": "mailto:nicholas.long@nrel.gov"      },       "identifier": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/efaf629a-2de6-4c76-8470-dc3c7db9bd42",       "accessLevel": "public",       "accessURL": "https://bcl.nrel.gov/",       "format": "application/unknown",       "license": "https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/",       "dataQuality": true,       "distribution": [        {          "@type": "dcat:Distribution",           "description": "DOE-019-2039840921",           "title": "Building Component Library",           "format": "HTML",           "accessURL": "https://bcl.nrel.gov/",           "mediaType": "text/html"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Annual average modeled wind speed (m/s) for Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands at a 100 meter hub height",       "description": "<span style=\"line-height: 16.8999996185303px;\">This is supplemental data to the 50 m height data set that was validated by NREL and wind energy meteorological consultants in 2007.        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Solar: hourly solar (direct normal (DNI), global horizontal (GHI), and diffuse) data for selected stations in Cuba from NREL",       "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each data file is a set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the [NREL](http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL) METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. Each container file contains up to 30 yearly files for one station, plus the Typical Meteorological Year (TMY) file for the selected station, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   The intended use of these data files is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. The yearly data may be suitable for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location, if enough years of data are present. The TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year.. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years.",       "keyword": [        "Cuba",         "DNI",         "GEF",         "GHI",         "NREL", "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each data file is a set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the [NREL](http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL \"NREL page in OpenEI\") METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. Each container file \r\ncontains up to 30 yearly files for one station, plus the Typical Meteorological Year (TMY) file for the selected station, plus \r\ndocumentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   The intended use of these data files is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. The yearly data may be suitable for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location, if enough years of data are present. The TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year.. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years.",       "keyword": [        "Bangladesh",         "DNI",         "GEF",         "GHI", Average)",       "description": "This shapefile represents the seasonal winter depth profile to reach water at a temperature of 20\u00baC.\r\n\r\nSea water cooling can be used for industrial or residential cooling needs where heat must be rejected. A typical resource for direct air-conditioning applications is no warmer than 8\u00baC, which has been established as a minimum value of interest for this study. Water at temperatures between 8\u00baC and 20\u00baC can be used to supplement air conditioning processes, or to reject heat from many other low temperature industrial processes. Water temperatures above 20\u00baC were not considered for this investigation as cost savings begin to break down as sea water temperature nears ambient temperatures. Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). buildings\r\nare usually estimated on an annual basis using annual average multipliers.  Using annual numbers provides a reasonable\r\nestimation of emissions, but it provides no indication of the temporal nature\r\nof the emissions.  Therefore, there is no\r\nway of understanding the impact on emissions from load\r\nshifting and peak shaving technologies such as thermal energy storage, on-site\r\nrenewable energy, and demand control.  \r\n\r\nThis project utilized GridViewTM, an\r\nelectric grid dispatch software package, to estimate hourly emission\r\nfactors for all of the [eGRID](http://www.epa.gov/cleanenergy/energy-resources/egrid/) subregions in the continental United\r\nStates. These factors took into account electricity imports and exports\r\nacross the eGRID subregion boundary, and included estimated\r\ntransmission and distribution (T) losses.  Emission types accounted for included carbon dioxide (CO2), nitrogen oxides (NOx), and sulfur dioxide (SO2).Data\r\nreported as part of this project include hourly average, minimum, and\r\nmaximum emission factors by month; that is, the average, minimum, and\r\nmaximum emission factor for the same hour of each day in a month.\r\nPlease note that the data are reported in lbs/MWh, where the MWh value\r\nreported is site electricity use (the actual electricity used at the\r\nbuilding) and the pounds of emissions reported are the emissions\r\ncreated at the generator to meet the building load, including\r\ntransmission and distribution losses.          "mediaType": "text/csv"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Comparative Analysis of Alternative Means for Removing Noncondensable Gases from Flashed-Steam Geothermal Power Plants:April 1999 - March 2000",       "description": "This dataset corresponds to the final report on a screening study to compare six methods of removing noncondensable gases from direct-use geo-thermal steam power plants. This report defines the study methodologies and compares the performance and economics of selected gas-removal systems. Recommendations are presented for follow-up investigations and implementation of some of the technologies discussed. The specific gas-removal methods include five vacuum system configurations using the conventional approach of evacuating gas/vapor mixtures from the power plant condenser system and a system for physical separation of steam and gases upstream of the power turbine. The study focused on flashed-steam applications, but the results apply equally well to flashed-steam and dry-steam geothermal power plant configurations. Two gas-removal options appear to offer profitable economic potential. The hybrid vacuum system configurations and the reboiler process yield positive net present value results over wide-ranging gas concentrations. The hybrid options look favorable for both low-temperature and high-temperature resource applications. The reboiler looks profitable for low-temperature resource applications for gas levels above about 20,000 parts per million by volume. A vacuum system configuration using a three-stage turbocompressor battery may be profitable for low-temperature resources, but results show that the hybrid system is more profitable. The biphase eductor alternative cannot be recommended for commercialization at this time. \r\nThe report is available from NREL's publication database.",       "keyword": [        "Geothermal data",         "NREL",         "geothermal",         "solar"      ],       "modified": "2015-08-21T20:50:28Z",       "publisher": {        "@type": "org:Organization",         "name": "National Renewable Energy Laboratory"      },       "bureauCode": [        "019:20"      ],       "programCode": [        "019:000"      ],       "contactPoint": {        "@type": "vcard:Contact",         "fn": "KC Hallett",         "hasEmail": "mailto:kathleen.hallett@nrel.gov"      },       "identifier": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fabc671c-14d1-4e6d-8cec-59541630fb05",       "accessLevel": "public",       "accessURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fabc671c-14d1-4e6d-8cec-59541630fb05/resource/fd435cbe-6113-4e04-ba5c-45448db7d730/download/28329data.xls",       "format": "application/vnd.ms-excel",       "license": "http://www.opendefinition.org/licenses/odc-pddl",       "dataQuality": true,       "distribution": [        {          "@type": "dcat:Distribution",           "description": "Download data",           "title": "Download data",           "format": "XLS",           "downloadURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fabc671c-14d1-4e6d-8cec-59541630fb05/resource/fd435cbe-6113-4e04-ba5c-45448db7d730/download/28329data.xls",           "mediaType": "application/vnd.ms-excel"        },         {          "@type": "dcat:Distribution",           "description": "Download report",           "title": "Download report",           "format": "PDF",           "downloadURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fabc671c-14d1-4e6d-8cec-59541630fb05/resource/2a4c5300-1786-4f61-8f4c-4a3f5a51acfc/download/28329report.pdf",           "mediaType": "application/pdf"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Technical Report - "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each data file is a set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the [NREL](http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL) METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. Each container file contains up to 30 yearly files for one station, plus the Typical Meteorological Year (TMY) file for the selected station, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   The intended use of these data files \r\nis for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and \r\nbuilding systems. The yearly data may be suitable for designing systems \r\nand their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a \r\nlocation, if enough years of data are present. The TMY consists of \r\nmonths selected from individual years and concatenated to form a \r\ncomplete year.. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not \r\nappropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY \r\nprovides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other \r\nmeteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system \r\ntypes and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not \r\nnecessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even \r\nthe next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical \r\nover a long period of time, such as 30 years.",       "keyword": [        "DNI",         "GHI",         "Ghana",         "NREL", Brazil from NREL",       "description": "(Abstract): Monthly average solar resource for horizontal flat-plate collectors for Brazil.\r\n\r\n(Purpose): Provide information on the solar resource potential for the data domain. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented horizontally.\r\n\r\n(Supplemental Information): These data provide monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximately 40 km by 40 km in size.  The solar resource value is represented as watt-hours per square meter per day for each month.  The data were developed from <a href=\"http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL\" title=\"\" target=\"_blank\">NREL's</a> Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model.  This model uses information on cloud cover, atmospheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface.   Existing ground measurement stations \r\nare used to validate the data where possible.  The modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell due to the uncertainties associated with meteorological input to the model.  The local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell as a result of terrain effects and other microclimate influences.    "format": "ZIP",           "downloadURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/cecf687d-28e3-4e27-b3a4-269a02acd8a0/resource/da98f469-6fb3-44f0-81cb-def9bdf870fa/download/globalwinddata199.zip",           "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Alaska Low Resolution Concentrating Solar Power Resource",       "description": "_Abstract:_  Monthly and annual average solar resource potential for Alaska.\r\n\r\n_Purpose:_  Provide information on the solar resource potential for Alaska. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented due south at an angle from horizontal equal to the latitude of the collector location.\r\n\r\n_Supplemental Information:_  This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximatley 40 km by 40 km in size. This data was developed from the Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model. The CSR model was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Maxwell, George and Wilcox (1998) and George and Maxwell (1999). This model uses information on cloud cover, atmostpheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. The cloud cover data used as input to the CSR model are an 7-year histogram (1985-1991) of monthly average cloud fraction provided for grid cells of approximately 40km x 40km in size. Thus, the spatial resolution of the CSR model output is defined by this database. The data are obtained from the National Climatic Data Center in Ashville, North Carolina, and were developed from the U.S. Air Force Real Time Nephanalysis (RTNEPH) program. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. The procedures for converting the collector at latitude tilt are described in Marion and Wilcox (1994). Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not avalible at a 40km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other micoclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain. Units are in watt hours.\r\n\r\nOther Citation Details:\r\n\r\nGeorge, R, and E. Maxwell, 1999: \"High-Resolution Maps of Solar Collector Performance Using A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1999 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Portland, ME. \r\n\r\nMaxwell, E, R. George and S. Wilcox, \"A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1998 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Albuquerque NM.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). Net Power (Summer Average)",       "description": "This shapefile represents seasonal summer average net power estimates.\r\n\r\nThe OTEC Plant model predicts the net power production at a specific location, given three inputs: surface temperature (\u00b0C), depth (m), and difference between warm surface water temperature and cold deep sea water temperature (\u0394T in \u00b0C) at the given depth, relative to the surface temperature.\r\n\r\nIn order to normalize values for the purposes of visualization of the OTEC resource around the world, a baseline plant design was used. The baseline 100MW Net Power design has been optimized for conditions indicative of the Hawai\u2018i OTEC resource. As such, power output as described by the results of this study is not optimized for local conditions (except in parts of Hawai\u2019i), but does provide guidance for site selection. Given the nominal plant power output of 100MW based on a competitive cost of electricity (Hawai\u2019i), any output exceeding this value represents significant potential. A large area of predicted 100 MW+ net power exists in many locations around the world, especially in areas with high energy costs.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). A typical resource for direct air-conditioning applications is no warmer than 8\u00baC, which has been established as a minimum value of interest for this study. Water at temperatures between 8\u00baC and 20\u00baC can be used to supplement air conditioning processes, or to reject heat from many other low temperature industrial processes. Water temperatures above 20\u00baC were not considered for this investigation as cost savings begin to break down as sea water temperature nears ambient temperatures. Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). A typical resource for direct air-conditioning applications is no warmer than 8\u00baC, which has been established as a minimum value of interest for this study. Water at temperatures between 8\u00baC and 20\u00baC can be used to supplement air conditioning processes, or to reject heat from many other low temperature industrial processes. Water temperatures above 20\u00baC were not considered for this investigation as cost savings begin to break down as sea water temperature nears ambient temperatures. Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). delta T (Summer Average)",       "description": "This shapefile represents seasonal summer average delta T estimates.\r\n\r\n\u0394T represents the difference in temperature (\u00b0C) between the warm and cold water sources used by an OTEC plant at a specific location. Warm water is defined uniformly as water at a depth of 20 m, while cold water is defined for each point by locating the depth that leads to the greatest annual net power when each depth and \u0394T along the thermocline are input into the power equation. This optimization balances power gained by obtaining colder water from deeper locations against power lost by transporting the water upward through a longer pipe.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). Warm water is defined uniformly as water at a depth of 20 m, while cold water is defined for each point by locating the depth that leads to the greatest annual net power when each depth and \u0394T along the thermocline are input into the power equation. This optimization balances power gained by obtaining colder water from deeper locations against power lost by transporting the water upward through a longer pipe.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). stations in Nepal from NREL",       "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each TMY is a data set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the NREL METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. The container file contains one TMY file for each selected station in the region, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   A TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year. The intended use is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years. Because they represent typical rather than extreme conditions, they are not suited for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location.", The toolkit helps energy planners, project developers, researchers and others identify areas of a country that show good potential for renewable energy projects. The toolkit displays renewable energy data along with information about the geography, location of population centers, borders, and transportation and power infrastructure.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe toolkit is integrated with HOMER, a power system simulation and optimization model, originally developed at NREL and currently owned by HOMER Energy LLC. HOMER integration with the toolkit makes it possible to automatically populate HOMER inputs using weather data from the toolkit to help you get started with your HOMER analysis. The toolkit also displays preliminary HOMER results that you can see without running the model.\r\n<br><br>\r\nNREL works with different funding partners to develop toolkits for different countries. Institutions in each country provide data for the toolkit, which NREL analyzes and prepares to meet the toolkit specifications. Geographic data for each country comes from different sources, including NREL's renewable resource database, resource assessment programs in each country, and government ministries and research institutions responsible for maintaining geographic datasets for the country.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFor a list of available Geospatial toolkits and more information about NREL's partners in developing the developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL). The toolkit helps energy planners, project developers, researchers and others identify areas of a country that show good potential for renewable energy projects. The toolkit displays renewable energy data along with information about the geography, location of population centers, borders, and transportation and power infrastructure.\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe toolkit is integrated with HOMER, a power system simulation and optimization model, originally developed at NREL and currently owned by HOMER Energy LLC. HOMER integration with the toolkit makes it possible to automatically populate HOMER inputs using weather data from the toolkit to help you get started with your HOMER analysis. The toolkit also displays preliminary HOMER results that you can see without running the model.\r\n<br><br>\r\nNREL works with different funding partners to develop toolkits for different countries. Institutions in each country provide data for the toolkit, which NREL analyzes and prepares to meet the toolkit specifications. Geographic data for each country comes from different sources, including NREL's renewable resource database, resource assessment programs in each country, and government ministries and research institutions responsible for maintaining geographic datasets for the country.\r\n<br><br>\r\nFor a list of available Geospatial toolkits and more information about NREL's partners in developing the     "mediaType": "text/plain"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Meteorology: typical meteorological year data for selected stations in China from NREL",       "description": "_(Abstract):_  Each TMY is a data set of hourly values of solar radiation and meteorological elements for a 1-year period. Solar radiation is modeled using the NREL METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. The container file contains one TMY file for each selected station in the region, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  Simulations\r\n\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_   A TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year. The intended use is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and \r\nbuilding systems. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even \r\nthe next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years. Because they represent typical rather than extreme conditions, they are not suited for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location.",     "mediaType": "text/plain"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Kenya Hourly DNI, GHI and Diffuse Solar Data",       "description": "#Abstract\r\nEach data file is a set of hourly values of solar radiation (DNI, GHI and diffuse) and meteorological elements for a 1-year period.  Solar radiation is modeled using the [NREL](http://en.openei.org/wiki/NREL \"NREL's OpenEI page\") METSTAT model, with surface observed cloud cover being the principal model input. Each container file contains up to 30 yearly files for one station, plus the Typical Meteorological Year (TMY) file for the selected station, plus documentation files and a TMY data reader file for use with Microsoft Excel.\r\n\r\n#Purpose\r\nSimulations\r\n\r\n#Supplemental Information\r\nThe intended use of these data files is for computer simulations of solar energy conversion systems and building systems. The yearly data may be suitable for designing systems and their components to meet the worst-case conditions occurring at a location, if enough years of data are present. The TMY consists of months selected from individual years and concatenated to form a complete year.. Because of the selection criteria, these TMYs are not appropriate for simulations of wind energy conversion systems. A TMY provides a standard for hourly data for solar radiation and other meteorological elements that permit performance comparisons of system types and configurations for one or more locations. A TMY is not necessarily a good indicator of conditions over the next year, or even the next 5 years. Rather, it represents conditions judged to be typical over a long period of time, such as 30 years.",       "keyword": [        "DNI",         "GEF",         "GHI",         "Kenya",         "NREL",         "SWERA",         "TILT",         "TMY",         "UNEP",         "hourly data",         "solar"      ],       "modified": "2015-08-21T20:48:16Z",       "publisher": {        "@type": "org:Organization",         "name": "National Renewable Energy Laboratory"      },       "bureauCode": [        "019:20"      ],       "programCode": [        "019:000"      ],       "contactPoint": {        "@type": "vcard:Contact",         "fn": "Nicholas Langle",         "hasEmail": "mailto:nicholas.langle@nrel.gov"      },       "identifier": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fc539cdb-1a66-477c-9273-b6d02c6233ee",       "accessLevel": "public",       "accessURL": "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/fc539cdb-1a66-477c-9273-b6d02c6233ee/resource/c0ff9460-0093-4579-bf10-2ea6bcee0028/download/kenyatmy.csv",       "format": "text/csv",       "license": "http://www.opendefinition.org/licenses/odc-pddl",       "spatial": "{\"type\":\"Polygon\",\"coordinates\":[[[33.616410249999944,-4.791188578805073],[42.05178100000012,-4.791188578805073],[42.05178100000012,5.050425698792842],[33.616410249999944,5.050425698792842],[33.616410249999944,-4.791188578805073]]]}",       "dataQuality": true,       "distribution": [        {          "@type": "dcat:Distribution",           "description": "This zip contains the following Typical Meteorological Year (TMY) data files:\r\n\r\n- readme_kenya.txt - Average)",       "description": "This shapefile represents the seasonal summer depth profile to reach water at a temperature of 8\u00baC.\r\n\r\nSea water cooling can be used for industrial or residential cooling needs where heat must be rejected. A typical resource for direct air-conditioning applications is no warmer than 8\u00baC, which has been established as a minimum value of interest for this study. Water at temperatures between 8\u00baC and 20\u00baC can be used to supplement air conditioning processes, or to reject heat from many other low temperature industrial processes. Water temperatures above 20\u00baC were not considered for this investigation as cost savings begin to break down as sea water temperature nears ambient temperatures. Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). Depth profiles for three water temperatures of interest: 8\u00baC, 14\u00baC and 20\u00baC were established to aid selection of optimal sites for sea water cooling. A cool shallow resource just off the coast where a need may exist presents significant opportunity for energy and cost savings.\r\n\r\nData were processed and converted to shapefile format by NREL for the [Ocean Thermal Extractable Energy Visualization](http://www.osti.gov/bridge/purl.cover.jsp?purl=/1055457/1055457.pdf)\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/ed7cc60f-638a-41e4-befa-54ced1546571/resource/11ebed76-9cd0-49ee-ac3c-73ab8cd0ae12/download/afggstlite295.zip",           "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Hawaii Low Resolution Concentrating Solar Power Resource",       "description": "_Abstract:_  Monthly and annual average solar resource potential for Hawaii.\r\n\r\n_Purpose:_  Provide information on the solar resource potential for Hawaii. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented due south at an angle from horizontal equal to the latitude of the collector location.\r\n\r\n_Supplemental Information:_  This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximately 40 km by 40 km in size. This data was developed from the Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model. The CSR model was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Maxwell, George and Wilcox (1998) and George and Maxwell (1999). This model uses information on cloud cover, atmostpheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. The cloud cover data used as input to the CSR model are an 7-year histogram (1985-1991) of monthly average cloud fraction provided for grid cells of approximately 40km x 40km in size. Thus, the spatial resolution of the CSR model output is defined by this database. The data are obtained from the National Climatic Data Center in Ashville, North Carolina, and were developed from the U.S. Air Force Real Time Nephanalysis (RTNEPH) program. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. The procedures for converting the collector at latitude tilt are described in Marion and Wilcox (1994). Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not avalible at a 40km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other micoclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain. \r\nUnits are in watt hours.\r\n\r\nOther Citation Details:\r\n\r\nGeorge, R, and E. Maxwell, 1999: \"High-Resolution Maps of Solar Collector Performance Using A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1999 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Portland, ME. \r\n\r\nMaxwell, E, R. George and S. Wilcox, \"A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1998 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Albuquerque NM.\r\n\r\n### License Info\r\nDISCLAIMER NOTICE\r\nThis GIS data was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (\"NREL\"), which is operated by the Alliance for Sustainable Energy, LLC for the U.S. Department of Energy (\"DOE\"). "http://en.openei.org/doe-opendata/dataset/431ea10f-0f6c-44d7-a438-ef882f31ed96/resource/0d90ee50-f773-4987-8428-c47eb7102112/download/hawaiicsplowresolution.zip",           "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "NREL GIS Data: Hawaii Low Resolution Photovoltaic Solar Resource",       "description": "_Abstract:_  Monthly and annual average solar resource potential for Hawaii.\r\n\r\n_Purpose:_  Provide information on the solar resource potential for Hawaii. The insolation values represent the average solar energy available to a flat plate collector, such as a photovoltaic panel, oriented due south at an angle from horizontal equal to the latitude of the collector location.\r\n\r\n_Supplemental Information:_  This data provides monthly average and annual average daily total solar resource averaged over surface cells of approximatley 40 km by 40 km in size. This data was developed from the Climatological Solar Radiation (CSR) Model. The CSR model was developed by the National Renewable Energy Laboratory for the U.S. Department of Energy. Specific information about this model can be found in Maxwell, George and Wilcox (1998) and George and Maxwell (1999). This model uses information on cloud cover, atmostpheric water vapor and trace gases, and the amount of aerosols in the atmosphere to calculate the monthly average daily total insolation (sun and sky) falling on a horizontal surface. The cloud cover data used as input to the CSR model are an 7-year histogram (1985-1991) of monthly average cloud fraction provided for grid cells of approximately 40km x 40km in size. Thus, the spatial resolution of the CSR model output is defined by this database. The data are obtained from the National Climatic Data Center in Ashville, North Carolina, and were developed from the U.S. Air Force Real Time Nephanalysis (RTNEPH) program. Atmospheric water vapor, trace gases, and aerosols are derived from a variety of sources. The procedures for converting the collector at latitude tilt are described in Marion and Wilcox (1994). Where possible, existing ground measurement stations are used to validate the data. Nevertheless, there is uncertainty associated with the meterological input to the model, since some of the input parameters are not avalible at a 40km resolution. As a result, it is believed that the modeled values are accurate to approximately 10% of a true measured value within the grid cell. Due to terrain effects and other micoclimate influences, the local cloud cover can vary significantly even within a single grid cell. Furthermore, the uncertainty of the modeled estimates increase with distance from reliable measurement sources and with the complexity of the terrain. \r\nUnits are in watt hours.\r\n\r\nOther Citation Details:\r\n\r\nGeorge, R, and E. Maxwell, 1999: \"High-Resolution Maps of Solar Collector Performance Using A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1999 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Portland, ME. \r\n\r\nMaxwell, E, R. George and S. Wilcox, \"A Climatological Solar Radiation Model\", Proceedings of the 1998 Annual Conference, American Solar Energy Society, Albuquerque NM. \r\n\r\nMarion, William and Stephen Wilcox, 1994: \"Solar Radiation Data Manual for Flat-plate and Concentrating Collectors\". "mediaType": "application/zip"        }      ]    },     {      "@type": "dcat:Dataset",       "title": "Integrated: Enhanced Geospatial Toolkit for Sri Lanka from NREL",       "description": "_(Abstract):_  Stand\u2013alone and easy to use geographic toolkit that allows non-GIS users to relate the renewable energy resource (solar and wind) data to other geographic data, such as land use, protected areas, elevation, etc.\r\n\r\n_(Purpose):_  The Solar and Wind Energy Resource Assessment (SWERA) Geospatial Toolkit (GsT) is a map-based software application that can be used for decision making and policy analysis in addition to planning for future energy projects. The SWERA application utilizes Geographical Information Systems (GIS) to develop common scenarios to evaluate potential locations for solar or wind energy plants.\r\n\r\n_(Supplemental Information):_ Enhancements to the GeoSpatial Toolkit (GsT) were funded by USAID's Southeast Asia Regional Initiative/Energy (SARI/E).  These enhancements include additional functionality and data development not available with the standard GeoSpatial Toolkit.\r\n\r\nFunctionality\r\n---------------------------\r\nThe additional functionality that has been added is a link from the GsT to the HOMER application, which provides analysis on system optimization.  The user will select a point on the map by clicking on it with a HOMER tool.  The tool will gather information on the wind, solar (global horizontal), elevation, and location to send to HOMER for analysis.  The tool will accept some user inputs and display a summary of the analysis results.  The user also has the option of opening the completed analysis directly in the HOMER application for additional options (using the \"Open HOMER File\" button).  Hydro data (if available) can be displayed in the tool window, but is not used by HOMER in its system optimization at this point.\r\nWhen the GsT is installed, it will also install the separate HOMER application with a 6 month license. After 6 months, the HOMER license will expire and the separate HOMER application will no longer run analyses.  THE LICENSE EXPIRATION WILL ONLY IMPACT THE \"Open HOMER File\" FUNCTIONALITY. The GsT will continue to run as usual and the \"Start HOMER\" button will continue to work.  However, when you click the \"Open HOMER File\" button, HOMER will only open files for \r\nviewing - you will no longer be able to make the HOMER application run an analysis.\r\nThe HOMER license can be renewed for free over the \r\ninternet.  You can renew your HOMER license and find out more about HOMER at this web address:\r\nhttp://www.nrel.gov/homer\r\n\r\nAdditional Data Development\r\n---------------------------\r\nMonthly Wind Resource Data:  The existing annual wind resource dataset has been expanded to include average wind speed and power for each month, annual average Weibull K shape parameter, annual average autocorrelation coefficient, and the annual diurnal pattern, peak hour, and pattern strength.  These parameters are needed for HOMER to synthesize an hourly wind speed for a representative year (8760 hours).\r\n\r\nHydro Resource Data:  A hydro resource dataset was developed as a separate task for SARI/E, and the results of that assessment have been incorporated for display within the GsT.  The hydro resource assessment provides annual and monthly estimates of average potential hydro power (kW).  The data was developed focusing on small hydro systems with small diversion distances, returning water to the stream within 200 m of the diversion point.\r\n\r\n---------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nThe GsT was completely redesigned and re-released in November 2010 to provide a more modern, easier-to-use interface with considerably faster analytical querying capabilities. The revised version of the Geospatial Toolkit for Sri Lanka is available using the following link:  http://www.nrel.gov/international/downloads/gst_srilanka.exe\r\n\r\nNOTE: Please use the provided link to access the most up to date software package and data.  The Sri Lanka GsT data were last updated in January 2011.  The attached zip file below is an archive and contains the previous version of the geospatial toolkit executable that has been replaced.\r\n\r\nPlease visit [Geospatial
